‘foreign, Welsh’. This form of the name was generally more common than   Welsh  , especially in Ireland, where it originally denoted a Welsh-speaking immigrant, in particular any of the Welshmen who arrived in the wake of Strongbow's Anglo-Norman invasion of 1170. In Ireland it is sometimes also a translation of <b>Breathnach</b> ‘Briton’.","English: in Yorkshire and Lancashire the name is sometimes a shortened form of   Walshaw  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walshe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eoin, Murph.","English and Irish: variant of   Walsh  ."]},{"name":"McBratney","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Breatnaigh</b> ‘son of the Briton’ (referring to the Welsh of Strathclyde). Compare   Walsh   and   Galbraith  ."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Walssh was born in 1345, in Purbeck, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Roger Le Waleys, was 35 and her mother, Johanna De Chisildene, was 34. She had at least 1 son with John Filliol. She died in 1383, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1345–1383":"1345–1383","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1403":"1352–1403","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1311–1355":"1311–1355","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","31 October 1375":"31. oktoober 1375","1416":"1416","Purbeck, Dorset, England":"Purbeck, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1345–1383":"1345–1383","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1403":"1352–1403","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1311–1355":"1311–1355","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","31 October 1375":"31. lokakuuta 1375","1416":"1416","Purbeck, Dorset, England":"Purbeck, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1345–1383":"1345–1383","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1403":"1352–1403","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1311–1355":"1311–1355","1403":"1403","1345":"1345","1355":"1355",